  {/* PROBLEM + MOTIVATION */}
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Problem & Motivation</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-start">
      <div class="text-gray-700 space-y-4">
        <p class="text-gray-600">
          Automated Fiber Placement (AFP) is a composite manufacturing process where fiber tape is laid
          along a prescribed path and compacted with a roller. The quality of layup depends heavily on
          repeatable contact force and consistent roller alignment relative to the mold surface.
        </p>

        <p class="text-gray-600">
          This project focused on the control problem at the heart of AFP: tracking a surface trajectory
          while maintaining stable interaction with the mold. Unlike free-space manipulation, AFP is
          contact-rich and sensitive to surface variation, compliance, and control-loop behavior.
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-600">
          <li>Track a path on (planar or curved) mold geometry</li>
          <li>Maintain controlled contact during compaction (roller-on-surface)</li>
          <li>Achieve compliant behavior while resisting disturbances</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <img
          src="/images/afp/example.jpg"
          alt="AFP example showing robot and layup concept"
          class="rounded-lg shadow-sm w-full"
        />

        {/* Optional: add this if you want a second explanatory visual */}
        <img
          src="/images/afp/roller-schematic.png"
          alt="AFP head schematic showing roller and material placement"
          class="rounded-lg shadow-sm w-full"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* SYSTEM OVERVIEW */}
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">System Overview</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-start">
      <div class="text-gray-700 space-y-4">
        <p class="text-gray-600">
          The system was implemented and validated in simulation using PyDrake. A UR5e arm was tasked
          with moving a roller end effector along a generated trajectory while interacting with a
          compliant mold surface using Drake’s contact modeling capabilities.
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-600">
          <li><span class="font-medium">Robot:</span> UR5e model running in Drake’s simulation environment</li>
          <li><span class="font-medium">End effector:</span> roller designed to impose and regulate contact</li>
          <li><span class="font-medium">Environment:</span> compliant mold surface represented as contact geometry</li>
          <li><span class="font-medium">Control goal:</span> trajectory tracking + stable force interaction via impedance control</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="text-gray-600">
          The architecture intentionally emphasized robust interaction behavior rather than purely
          position-based tracking, since AFP depends on consistent compaction forces and stable surface
          contact under small disturbances and modeling error.
        </p>
